      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument about disincentives is a common, yet often overstated, critique from those who favor minimal government intervention. When benefits are structured correctly, they act as a springboard, not a hammock, enabling people to seek better opportunities. The real issue is not the existence of the safety net, but the bureaucratic hurdles and punitive clawback rates that make the transition back to work unnecessarily difficult.",
      "source": "target",
